## The dunders that earn their keep

```python
class Item:
    def __init__(self, name, qty):
        self.name, self.qty = name, qty
    def __repr__(self):
        return f"Item({self.name!r}, {self.qty})"   # debugging gold
    def __eq__(self, other):
        return (self.name, self.qty) == (other.name, other.qty)
    def __lt__(self, other):
        return self.qty < other.qty                  # enables sorted(items)
    def __len__(self): ...
    def __contains__(self, x): ...

# or skip the boilerplate:
from dataclasses import dataclass, field

@dataclass
class Item:
    name: str
    qty: int = 0
    tags: list = field(default_factory=list)   # NEVER tags: list = []
```

@dataclass writes __init__, __repr__, and __eq__ for you. On a timed screen it's legitimate speed; just remember field(default_factory=list) for mutable defaults.
